1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:04,848
The Task Upgrade Scorecard turns those four properties into four practical gates.

2
00:00:04,798 --> 00:00:07,817
Gate one asks whether the output is concrete.

3
00:00:07,817 --> 00:00:13,173
If you only need an explanation, comparison, or brainstorm, keep the task in chat.

4
00:00:13,173 --> 00:00:16,067
If you need a finished artifact, continue.

5
00:00:16,067 --> 00:00:19,846
Gate two asks whether the work forms a contiguous action chain.

6
00:00:19,846 --> 00:00:26,221
The agent must be able to move from source material to action to result without repeatedly waiting for hidden information.

7
00:00:26,221 --> 00:00:34,125
If the chain is broken by unavailable systems or undocumented decisions, use AI as a copilot while the human performs the missing steps.

8
00:00:34,125 --> 00:00:37,442
Gate three asks whether progress produces evidence.

9
00:00:37,442 --> 00:00:47,413
Each important step should return a signal that can change the plan: a test result, schema check, source citation, preview, reconciliation total, or provider response.

10
00:00:47,413 --> 00:00:53,173
If evidence exists but judgment is still difficult, use a supervised agent and add checkpoints.

11
00:00:53,173 --> 00:00:57,009
Gate four asks whether permissions and consequences are bounded.

12
00:00:57,009 --> 00:00:59,875
Reversible work can continue automatically.

13
00:00:59,875 --> 00:01:03,769
Irreversible work should stop before the action and request approval.

14
00:01:03,769 --> 00:01:07,605
A capable agent does not need unlimited authority to be useful.

15
00:01:07,605 --> 00:01:13,259
This scorecard is a practical synthesis of the research evidence, not a table copied from OpenAI.

16
00:01:13,259 --> 00:01:19,000
Its purpose is to translate the shift from conversation to delegation into a decision you can use today.

17
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:21,192
Consider a spreadsheet cleanup.

18
00:01:21,192 --> 00:01:29,211
The output is a corrected workbook, the inputs are available, formulas and totals provide feedback, and the original file can be preserved.

19
00:01:29,211 --> 00:01:33,278
That task can often reach supervised or delegated execution.

20
00:01:33,278 --> 00:01:35,701
Now consider publishing a newsletter.

21
00:01:35,701 --> 00:01:41,461
Research, drafting, formatting, link checks, and preview generation can be delegated.

22
00:01:41,461 --> 00:01:48,298
The final external send is high impact, so the workflow should stop for approval even if every preparation step passes.

23
00:01:48,298 --> 00:01:56,961
A research task fits when sources are accessible, claims remain linked to evidence, uncertainty is visible, and the deliverable has acceptance criteria.

24
00:01:56,961 --> 00:02:03,682
Asking an agent to decide a high-stakes policy from incomplete sources does not become safe merely because the task is long.

25
00:02:03,682 --> 00:02:06,288
The four work modes are therefore simple.

26
00:02:06,288 --> 00:02:08,269
Use chat for answers.

27
00:02:08,269 --> 00:02:11,807
Use a copilot when the human still owns the action chain.

28
00:02:11,807 --> 00:02:16,894
Use a supervised agent when the chain works but checkpoints or judgment remain important.

29
00:02:16,894 --> 00:02:22,250
Use a delegated workflow when all four gates hold and the procedure is stable enough to repeat.

30
00:02:22,250 --> 00:02:23,788
Chapter recap.

31
00:02:23,788 --> 00:02:27,185
First, upgrade the work mode one gate at a time.

32
00:02:27,185 --> 00:02:31,125
Second, keep irreversible actions behind explicit approval.

33
00:02:31,125 --> 00:02:36,000
Third, choose the least autonomous mode that can reliably produce the required outcome.
